    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In Japanese architecture, an interior space that may have evolved historically from the private altars of Zen Buddhist monks, used for the display of devotional objects; then later as elevated seating for warriors or dignitaries. The most recent use of  the space in Japanese houses is for the display of flower arrangements and scrolls that set the mood of the tea ceremony, or other art objects.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
